reference: Zbyryt, A., et al. (2021). "Behavioural responses of adult and young White Storks Ciconia ciconia in nests to an unmanned aerial vehicle." Acta Ornithologica 55(2): 243-251.
title: Behavioural responses of adult and young White Storks Ciconia ciconia in nests to an unmanned aerial vehicle.
approach_description: Launched from 30m, acended to 18m at 1m/s then directly approach birds nesting on 9m high powerpoles at 5m/s.
response_measure_description: used glmm with FID as response and breeding stage, number of fledgelings, temperature, nest location, nest id (re) as predictors.

reference: Rümmler, M.-C., et al. (2021). "Effects of UAV overflight height, UAV type, and season on the behaviour of emperor penguin adults and chicks." Remote Sensing Applications: Society and Environment 23: 100558.
title: Effects of UAV overflight height, UAV type, and season on the behaviour of emperor penguin adults and chicks.
approach_description: launched 100m horizontal distance and 15m vertically above, ascended to test altitude of 145m, 95m, 70m, 45m, 35m, or 20m, overflew birds.
response_measure_description: recorded penguins and categorised reactions as vigilance, flipper-flapping, moving or sleeping for all visible birds once every 2s for 20s starting 10s after minimum uav approach distance for each flight. Fit Kruskal-Wallis-tests for flight height, uav, day.
result_description: Siginificantly more vigilance than controls at altitudes below 45m. Siginificantly more flapping than controls at altitudes below 70m. More disturbance observed than with a fixed wing UAV.
html: emporer penguinAptenodytes forsteriadult breedingdji phantom 4 prolaunched 100m horizontal distance and 15m vertically above, ascended to test altitude of 145m, 95m, 70m, 45m, 35m, or 20m, overflew birds.proportional behaviourSiginificantly more vigilance than controls at altitudes below 45m. Siginificantly more flapping than controls at altitudes below 70m. More disturbance observed than with a fixed wing UAV.Rümmler, M.-C., et al. (2021) Rümmler, M.-C., et al. (2021). "Effects of UAV overflight height, UAV type, and season on the behaviour of emperor penguin adults and chicks." Remote Sensing Applications: Society and Environment 23: 100558.

reference: Rümmler, M.-C., et al. (2021). "Emperor penguin reactions to UAVs: first observations and comparisons with effects of human approach." Remote Sensing Applications: Society and Environment: 100545.
title: Emperor penguin reactions to UAVs: first observations and comparisons with effects of human approach.
approach_description: takeoff 100m horizontally and 15m vertically from birds. Flew to 20m asl then overflew the birds.
response_measure_description: recorded penguins and categorised reactions as vigilance, flipper-flapping, sleeping for all visible birds once every 3s in video. Used glme with behaviour as response and distance and time from closest approach as predictor, video frame within clip as random factor
result_description: Significantly more vigilance and flapping than control. Behaviour was not significantly impacted by horizontal distance. Reactions lasted about 40s. Less reaction than vertical drone or human approach, and less than chicks.
html: emporer penguinAptenodytes forsteriadult breedingdji phantom 4 protakeoff 100m horizontally and 15m vertically from birds. "Emperor penguin reactions to UAVs: first observations and comparisons with effects of human approach." Remote Sensing Applications: Society and Environment: 100545.

reference: Mesquita, G. P., et al. (2021). "Measuring disturbance at swift breeding colonies due to the visual aspects of a drone: a quasi-experiment study." Current Zoology 67(2): 157-163.
title: Measuring disturbance at swift breeding colonies due to the visual aspects of a drone: a quasi-experiment study.
approach_description: launched at least 100m from birds, approached at altitudes between 40m and -5m (respective to cliff nesting birds) and distances of 50-25m.
response_measure_description: Nonlinear Gompertz regression between diagonal distance and % disturbed of swift, Nonlinear power regression between % disturbed of swifts and return time.
result_description: closer flights produced higher disturbance, below 20% at distances above 50m, above 60% when less than 40m. Flee time was longer when more of the birds where disturbed. High disturbance flights had a flee time of 23.5+-2.4min, medium disturbance had 12+-2.9min, low disturbance had immediate return time.

citation: Frixione, M. G. and C. Salvadeo (2021)
approach_description: Takeoff to 20m at varying distances between 300 and 15m.
result_description: Adult birds mobbed the drone during ascent to 20m. Mobbing increased with distance from urban areas. Groups with less adults mobbed more readily. Drone launch distance, noise, color, season and number of juveniles did not increase mobbing.

reference: Weston, M. A., et al. (2020). "Escape responses of terrestrial and aquatic birds to drones: Towards a code of practice to minimize disturbance." Journal of applied ecology 57(4): 777-785.
title: Escape responses of terrestrial and aquatic birds to drones: Towards a code of practice to minimize disturbance.
approach_description: Launch between 40m and 155m, then overflight at 10m or 4m
result_description: FID=46m (n=26). Escape response more likely than aggression. Birds were 14.6% more likely to flee if the drone was at 4m rather than 10m. Fleeing occurred 88.4% of the time at 4m and 77.1% at 10m. Starting distance positively correlated with FID. Altitude did not affect FID. approach_description: Launch between 40m and 155m, then overflight at 10m or 4m
result_description: FID=36m (n=43). Escape response more likely than aggression. Birds were 14.6% more likely to flee if the drone was at 4m rather than 10m. Fleeing occurred 88.4% of the time at 4m and 77.1% at 10m. Starting distance positively correlated with FID. Altitude did not affect FID. Longer starting distances made birds less likely to flee during both launch and approach. Drone launch caused fleeing 20% of the time. <5% probability of fleeing when >100m.
